-- 
Light Louisiana Sweet Oil Gains as Brent-WTI Gap Fluctuates

-- B y   A a r o n   C l a r k
-- 
2011-07-11T16:55:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-11/light-louisiana-sweet-oil-gains-as-brent-wti-gap-fluctuates.html
The premium for Light Louisiana
Sweet crude in the U.S. Gulf gained while sour crudes weakened
and the gap between benchmarks West Texas Intermediate and Brent
hovered near a record.  The gap between WTI and its European counterpart increased
17 cents to $21.96 a barrel as of 12:36 p.m. in  New York . The
spread settled at a record high of $22.29 a barrel June 15.  When Brent gains versus WTI, it strengthens the value of
low-sulfur U.S. grades that compete with West African oil priced
against the European benchmark.  Light Louisiana Sweet’s premium increased 90 cents to
$19.20 a barrel over WTI as of 12:01 p.m. in New York, according
to data compiled by Bloomberg. Heavy Louisiana Sweet was
unchanged $18.60 a barrel over the benchmark.  Among sour, or high-sulfur, grades, the premium for Mars
Blend lost 50 cents to $13.50 a barrel, while Poseidon’s premium
narrowed 60 cents to $13.40 over WTI.  Southern Green Canyon’s premium lost 50 cents to $12.50 a
barrel over WTI. West Texas Sour’s discount was unchanged at $1.
Thunder Horse’s premium lost $1 to $19.  The premium for Syncrude widened 10 cents to $8.75.
Syncrude is a light, low-sulfur synthetic oil derived from the
tar sands in  Alberta .  The discount for Western Canada Select widened 5 cents to
$20.20 a barrel.  To contact the reporter on this story:
